  "prompt": "Do Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use cumulative acknowledgements or an acknowledgement for every individual packet?",
  "response": "Go-Back-N ARQ and Selective Repeat ARQ use different techniques for acknowledgements due to their differences in handling errors and retransmissions.\n\n### Go-Back-N ARQ:\nIn Go-Back-N ARQ, cumulative acknowledgements are used. When a receiver sends an acknowledgement, it acknowledges all packets up to a certain sequence number, indicating that it has correctly received all packets up to that point. If packet n is acknowledged, it means all packets up to packet n have been correctly received. If a packet with sequence number n is lost or damaged, the receiver will not acknowledge any subsequent packets until it correctly receives packet n. Consequently, the sender must retransmit packet n and all subsequent packets.\n\n### Selective Repeat ARQ:\nSelective Repeat ARQ uses individual acknowledgements for each packet. This means the receiver acknowledges each packet separately. If a packet with sequence number n is lost or damaged, only that specific packet needs to be retransmitted, rather than all subsequent packets. This allows for more efficient use of the network bandwidth compared to Go-Back-N ARQ, as only lost packets are retransmitted, not potentially multiple correctly received packets.\n\nIn summary:\n- **Go-Back-N ARQ** uses cumulative acknowledgements.\n- **Selective Repeat ARQ** uses individual acknowledgements for each packet.",
